"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:8.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">8.2</span> Cart, wagon</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">גַּלְגַּל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(galgal)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek23:24\">EZK 23:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek26:10\">EZK 26:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עֲגָלָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘agalah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen45:19\">GEN 45:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen45:21\">GEN 45:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen45:27\">GEN 45:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen46:5\">GEN 46:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:3\">NUM 7:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:3\">NUM 7:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:6\">NUM 7:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:7\">NUM 7:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:8\">NUM 7:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:7\">1SA 6:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:7\">1SA 6:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:8\">1SA 6:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:10\">1SA 6:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:11\">1SA 6:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:14\">1SA 6:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam6:14\">1SA 6:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam6:3\">2SA 6:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam6:3\">2SA 6:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr13:7\">1CH 13:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr13:7\">1CH 13:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps46:10\">PSA 46:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa5:18\">ISA 5:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa28:27\">ISA 28:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa28:28\">ISA 28:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:13\">AMO 2:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צָב, עֲגָלָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsav, ‘egloth tsav)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:3\">NUM 7:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:3\">NUM 7:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa66:20\">ISA 66:20</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἅμαξα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(hamaxa)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt15:11\">JDT 15:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir33:5\">SIR 33:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">καρρον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(karron)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Esd5:53\">1ES 5:53</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ῥέδη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(rhedē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev18:13\">REV 18:13</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0035_wagon_model.jpg\" alt=\"Drawing of a wagon model\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Drawing of a wagon model (© Deutsche Bibelgesellschaft, Stuttgart by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>The wagon was a two or four-wheeled carriage or cart used for travel or the transport of loads. Such vehicles were usually made of wood. They were pulled by draft animals, usually oxen, donkeys, or horses. These animals were attached to a long pole that was in turn attached to the front of the wagon. The upper section of the wagon was often formed by crossed wooden bars in the shape of a cage.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Wagons and carts in the Bible were always pulled by animals. Translators should avoid any word for “wagon” that indicates a vehicle propelled by an engine.</p>\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0066_cart_with_yoke_of_oxen.png\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:3\">NUM 7:3</a>: The meaning of the Hebrew phrase <em>‘egloth tsav</em> here is uncertain. Most translators and commentators say something like “covered wagons” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>). These would be wagons as described above with a cloth covering the items carried in each wagon. Such a wagon might resemble a tortoise or turtle, which is a meaning of the Hebrew word <em>tsav</em>.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek23:24\">EZK 23:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek26:10\">EZK 26:10</a>: The Hebrew word <em>galgal</em> is literally “wheel.” In the context of these verses, it is clear that this is a metonym for a vehicle with wheels, that is, a cart or wagon.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Esd5:53\">1ES 5:53</a>: In this verse some Greek manuscripts have the word <em>chara</em> (“joy”), which makes no sense in this context. One manuscript has the word <em>karron</em>, meaning “wagon” as described above.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
